	abstract = {In the absence of codified design provisions, the design of concrete encasements in corrugated steel web (CSW) girders is still predominantly governed by empirical approaches, which often results in conservative or suboptimal design solutions. This study presents an intelligent optimization method for concrete encasement integrating finite element analysis (FEA) and machine learning. A sample database was established using experimentally validated FEA simulations. Given the constraint of limited sample size caused by computationally expensive simulations, a Generalized Regression Neural Network (GRNN) model, with hyperparameter automatically tuned via Particle Swarm Optimization (PSO), was developed to predict shear performance. The model's predictive mechanism was further interpreted using SHapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP) analysis. Results show that while a conventional backpropagation neural network overfitted the small dataset in this study, the optimized-GRNN achieved high predictive accuracy with excellent generalization. Furthermore, PSO exhibited a computational efficiency nearly three times greater than that of the Genetic Algorithm for hyperparameter optimization. The optimized concrete encasement design enhanced shear performance of prismatic and tapered girders by 44.95 % and 46.22 %, respectively, outperforming the traditional enumeration method by a factor of 2.07–2.57. SHAP analysis provided clear, quantitative guidance on the influence of design parameters, identifying optimal dimensional ranges for practical application. The proposed optimization framework offers an effective solution for engineering optimization problems under small-sample scenarios. © 2025 Institution of Structural Engineers. Published by Elsevier Ltd. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies.},
	type = {Article},
	publication_stage = {Final},
