	abstract = {A multi-objective optimization based on roll center compensation is proposed to balance the yaw control accuracy and energy efficiency of the underwater glider (UG) in complex marine environments. A simulation model for the yaw control was established to quantify the impact of parameters on the controller energy consumption indices and motion accuracy index, involving the on-time ratio and average regulation quantity of the roll motor and the average heading error within the single profile. The simulation model was verified with sea trial data. With energy consumption and heading accuracy indices as the objectives function, we devise a guided multi-objective optimization built upon NSGA-II framework. Population initialization is driven by Spearman' correlation, and Sobol' sensitivity are deeply embedded into adaptive crossover and mutation operators. Compared with conventional NSGA-II under identical diversity indicators, the guided NSGA-II achieves markedly faster convergence, which sacrifices extreme solutions to achieve dimension-reduced decision-making. Furthermore, according to the varying priorities on energy consumption or heading accuracy for different tasks, the objective weights are dynamically adjusted. The sequential quadratic programming is introduced to locally refine the Pareto frontier and outputting the optimal parameter configuration adaptively. This study provides a practical engineering optimization paradigm for the UGs' yaw controller. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd},
